<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 2:6<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2561f160630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>2.</label.designator><headtext>Witnesses</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I25623f80630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.designator>A.</label.designator><headtext>Subpoenas; Attendance</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05b9682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>2:6.</label.designator><headtext>Failure to attend</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>When a witness fails to obey a subpoena, the court may secure a witnesses&apos; presence through attachment for contempt[<footnote.reference refid="Ic160b3d07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] and hold him in custody or require him to post bond for his appearance. <eos/><bos/>Additionally, the court may punish the failure to appear in the form of a fine not exceeding $300 and by imprisonment not exceeding 20 days.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic160dae07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic160b3d07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Attachment is the act or process of taking, apprehending, or seizing persons or property, by virtue of a writ, summons, or other judicial order, and bringing the same into the custody of the court for the purpose of securing satisfaction of the judgment ultimately to be entered in the action. <eos/><bos/>Black&apos;s Law Dictionary (9th ed.).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic160dae07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018079" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-13-26" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id0e263407fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-13-26</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018079" w-serial-number="2027724188" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id0e2d8727fbf11ea988285db8533e975">In re J.D., 316 Ga. App. 19, 728 S.E.2d 698 (2012)</cite.query> (determination by court that a witness is in contempt of court by failing to comply with a subpoena is within the court&apos;s discretion and it will only be overruled upon gross abuse of discretion).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 2:6<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
